    "content": null,
    "shortSummaryAdmin": "This first lesson introduces students to one of the foundations of English—the alphabet. It targets a skill that learners often struggle with for years: recognizing and producing the basic sounds of the language. The lesson builds familiarity with English phonetics, sets the stage for future pronunciation work, and helps the learner get used to Raichel’s voice and teaching style.",
    "shortSummaryStudent": "Your very first step in English: learning the alphabet the right way. Get to know the sounds, warm up your ears, and meet Raichel’s voice.",
    "courseOrganizationGroup": "6 Groups",
    "slideContents": "Intro; 3 Text; Activity; Text; 6 Activity; 3 Text; Activity; Text; Lesson Exam; Finale",
    "groupingStrategySummary": "To guide the learner through small, focused steps: introduction, application, pronunciation, L1→L2 challenges, and listening practice.",
    "activityTypes": [
      "AISpeak; 7 AISpeakStudentRepeat; AISpeakStudentChoose"
    ],
    "activityDescription": "The learner starts by just listening, then practices listening and repeating with a pronunciation score, and ends with one more listening round.",
    "signatureMetaphors": "A sounds like “é”; E is said with a smile; I as in “I” (je); AI ≠ IA; G and J are reversed; R like “Are you?”; double-v in French, double-U in English.",
    "mainGrammarTopics": "N/A",
    "pronunciationFocus": "A-Z",
    "vocabularyTheme": "The alphabet",
    "l1L2Issues": "Most people learn the alphabet once and then forget it, which makes spelling difficult later.\nA and I are often confused.\nE and I are often confused.\nG and J are often confused.\nR sounds closer to the French “r”.\nU is tricky — learners need to flatten their tongue.\nTo remember W: “double U”.\nZ is often said as “zed” (British), but in American English it’s “zee”.",
    "prerequisites": "Knowing the Latin letters; the alphabet.",
    "learningObjectives": "To become aware of English sounds and the alphabet, and the specific difficulties for French learners; to be able to hear and pronounce the alphabet correctly with support; to develop initial awareness of English pronunciation.",
    "notesForTeacherOrAI": "There is no need for perfection here."
  },
